Encapsulation in C# (Simple Summary)

Encapsulation means hiding internal data and allowing access only through methods or properties.

👉 In simple words:
“Protect your data and control how it is used.”

🔸 How it works in C#

Use private variables (fields) → hide data

Use public properties (get/set) → control access

🔸 Example:
class Student
{
    private int age;   // hidden data

    public int Age     // property
    {
        get { return age; }
        set
        {
            if (value > 0)
                age = value;
        }
    }
}

✔ Here:

age is hidden

Access only through Age property

Validation is applied

🔹 Why Encapsulation?

Protects data 🔒

Improves security

Makes code flexible & maintainable

Allows validation before setting values

🔥 Top Interview Questions & Answers
1. What is encapsulation?

👉 Encapsulation is wrapping data and methods into a single unit and restricting direct access using access modifiers.

2. How do you achieve encapsulation in C#?

👉 By using:

Private fields

Public properties (get/set)

3. What are access modifiers used in encapsulation?

👉

private → restrict access

public → allow controlled access

protected, internal → partial access

4. What is a property in C#?

👉 A property is a method used to get or set the value of a private field.

5. Difference between field and property?

👉

Field → stores data

Property → controls access to data

6. What is automatic property?
public int Age { get; set; }

👉 No need to declare a separate field manually.

7. Can we make a property read-only?
public int Age { get; private set; }

👉 Yes, by using private set

8. What is data hiding?

👉 Hiding internal data from outside access — main concept of encapsulation.

9. Why is encapsulation important?

👉 It prevents misuse of data and keeps the program secure and clean.
